1
00:00:03,287 --> 00:00:32,822
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:33,207 --> 00:00:34,889
and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:36,210 --> 00:00:39,433
I just want to say a few words about Sangha.

4
00:00:42,036 --> 00:00:54,811
The word Sangha is traditionally, or in the East anyway, it only refers to the monastic orders, the monks and the nuns.

5
00:00:56,134 --> 00:01:02,420
But in the West, it's become a sort of self-referential word, where Buddhists refer to themselves as the Sangha.

6
00:01:03,176 --> 00:01:08,245
So it also has been widened out really to include everybody.

7
00:01:08,784 --> 00:01:15,835
And that shows the effect of the secularization of Buddhism and the role of lay people.

8
00:01:16,697 --> 00:01:21,543
But I just want to take you back to the beginning just to show you how it sort of began.

9
00:01:21,563 --> 00:01:28,694
So when the Buddha decided that he would teach, so there was some doubt in his mind, maybe...

10
00:01:29,114 --> 00:01:40,643
over the subtlety of the teaching who knows but anyway he went back to his companions and the first two talks where he introduces his teaching it seems all of them became fully liberated

11
00:01:42,394 --> 00:01:46,460
We have to presume that they'd done a lot of work beforehand, like he had.

12
00:01:46,481 --> 00:01:55,335
I mean, he'd done all the practices of concentration, practices of self-mortification, which he didn't gain much from, apart from suffering.

13
00:01:56,578 --> 00:02:03,789
And then, of course, he went off by himself, and his search turned around upon itself.

14
00:02:03,868 --> 00:02:05,652
So instead of seeking happiness...

15
00:02:06,221 --> 00:02:09,126
He began to investigate how he was causing suffering.

16
00:02:09,145 --> 00:02:13,051
And it was that that led him to his awakening.

17
00:02:13,413 --> 00:02:15,276
And that's why we say he self-awakened.

18
00:02:16,336 --> 00:02:19,162
There was lots of practice at that time.

19
00:02:19,723 --> 00:02:29,176
Lots of men, mainly men, but also some women, who were leaving society and living as salmoners, as the homeless ones.

20
00:02:30,338 --> 00:02:32,222
So it wasn't he started a tradition.

21
00:02:32,241 --> 00:02:33,663
It had been long there.

22
00:02:33,847 --> 00:03:03,752
within that society it was all part of a great movement in that society politically there was a movement away from sort of tribal governance where you had elders and you had a chief elder so that was like the Buddha's father of the Sakya tribe and then it was moving towards monarchy so actually the Sakyas this little group of people

23
00:03:04,187 --> 00:03:10,764
just on the edge of Nepal, under the Himalayas, were under the local king of Kusala, of Kosala.

24
00:03:12,108 --> 00:03:14,252
That would have been Pasenadi at that time.

25
00:03:14,272 --> 00:03:15,094
So they were vassals.

26
00:03:15,836 --> 00:03:19,425
In other words, the system was becoming what we would recognize as medieval.

27
00:03:20,408 --> 00:03:20,508
Okay?

28
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:31,872
So when he began to teach, certain people, men at first, but then women, wanted to join him.

29
00:03:32,473 --> 00:03:34,475
And we call it the first ordination.

30
00:03:34,515 --> 00:03:37,120
He just said, ehi passico, which means come and try.

31
00:03:39,522 --> 00:03:44,808
There's a story about him rejecting women for the order.

32
00:03:44,941 --> 00:04:02,393
which I'm sure you've come across, where these court ladies, his stepmother, stepmother, can't remember who else, they came to join the order and to prove that they were up to the sort of

33
00:04:02,913 --> 00:04:06,175
raw life of the monastic order.

34
00:04:06,657 --> 00:04:15,824
You know, where you just live out in the forest, really, without any of the commodities of life.

35
00:04:16,605 --> 00:04:20,550
And when he came to them, he didn't think they'd make it.

36
00:04:21,211 --> 00:04:22,391
So he denies entry.

37
00:04:22,831 --> 00:04:26,295
And it's only when Ananda says to him, do you think women can become liberated?

38
00:04:26,555 --> 00:04:27,737
And he says, yes.

39
00:04:28,677 --> 00:04:29,879
And so he accepts them.

40
00:04:29,899 --> 00:04:31,940
But there's definitely...

41
00:04:32,274 --> 00:04:39,103
there's definitely little tales in the scriptures that he was accepting women long before that.

42
00:04:39,124 --> 00:04:46,934
So this is really, I suppose, the growth of, well, the effect of patrimony on society, even on the order.

43
00:04:48,617 --> 00:04:56,427
So he was accepting people, and then once he had a group of men and women who were fully liberated,

44
00:04:57,149 --> 00:05:15,175
the ordination procedure was to take refuge in him as the teacher, as the living embodiment of the Dharma, the teaching he was giving, and then the Sangha, which were these people who had intuited Nibbana at some level, and some of them were fully liberated.

45
00:05:16,656 --> 00:05:19,442
And that's become the lay ordination now.

46
00:05:19,541 --> 00:05:30,483
So when somebody wants to join the Buddhist religion, the Buddhist faith or whatever, you would go through a little ceremony and I'll come back to that.

47
00:05:30,502 --> 00:05:37,415
But then of course after about 20 years there were men and women who joined who weren't quite at the usual standard and were doing terrible and naughty things.

48
00:05:38,036 --> 00:05:39,980
So we had to establish rules.

49
00:05:40,500 --> 00:05:43,024
And it shows that he was very much a pragmatist.

50
00:05:43,043 --> 00:05:49,172
He didn't have some sort of ideal as to where he wanted the order to be.

51
00:05:50,173 --> 00:05:59,887
The rules came as the monks and nuns did something which was considered to be not right, not correct.

52
00:06:00,226 --> 00:06:07,096
Some of them were like thieving, any sexual intercourse.

53
00:06:07,757 --> 00:06:09,259
All that was

54
00:06:09,610 --> 00:06:11,713
I mean, monks made that mistake.

55
00:06:12,192 --> 00:06:16,619
And the first monk was, he didn't have the penalty of being kicked out of the order.

56
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:21,564
And then it goes all the way down to having things you shouldn't have.

57
00:06:22,125 --> 00:06:27,451
And so there are ceremonies where you give it up, where you have to hand it back, things like that.

58
00:06:27,752 --> 00:06:35,060
So you've got 227 of these rules and many more, which were created as the order went along.

59
00:06:35,327 --> 00:06:39,595
So when you look at them, they're sectioned out in order of seriousness.

60
00:06:40,516 --> 00:06:46,625
But they're all higgledy-piggledy, and some of them don't pertain anymore, like not to sit on woolen rugs.

61
00:06:47,386 --> 00:06:54,016
So presumably wool in those days was something quite precious.

62
00:06:54,737 --> 00:07:00,286
So the ordination then became quite complicated.

63
00:07:00,786 --> 00:07:04,052
People were joining because they were in debt to the government.

64
00:07:04,689 --> 00:07:07,173
So you couldn't join if you were in debt.

65
00:07:07,833 --> 00:07:15,541
There was a physician called Jivaka, who was very famous at the time, who offered his medical services free to order members.

66
00:07:16,122 --> 00:07:19,365
So sick men and women joined the order in order to get this free.

67
00:07:21,728 --> 00:07:24,011
That sounds pretty straightforward, doesn't it?

68
00:07:24,031 --> 00:07:26,213
So you can't join the order if you're sick.

69
00:07:26,994 --> 00:07:29,196
Now that's not an absolute rule.

70
00:07:29,362 --> 00:07:33,247
If you join a particular group of monks or nuns, they can decide to accept you.

71
00:07:33,869 --> 00:07:46,408
But if they think your illness is not going to undermine them financially or physically, you have to look after people.

72
00:07:46,427 --> 00:07:49,653
But once you're in, then really you have to be looked after.

73
00:07:50,394 --> 00:07:51,014
There's no way.

74
00:07:52,057 --> 00:07:54,642
And of course they didn't do that at that time sometimes.

75
00:07:54,663 --> 00:08:03,500
And when the Buddha came across somebody who was really sick and because it was diarrhoea and vomiting and all that, nobody wanted to treat him.

76
00:08:03,521 --> 00:08:04,101
So he did it.

77
00:08:04,403 --> 00:08:05,324
He did it with an anger.

78
00:08:06,005 --> 00:08:11,918
And then he turns to the monk and says, well, you know, you haven't got a mother and father who's going to look after you if you don't look after people.

79
00:08:11,958 --> 00:08:13,019
He berated them that way.

80
00:08:14,771 --> 00:08:16,254
So you have the order.

81
00:08:16,293 --> 00:08:20,802
Now, the order in the East still fills a real role.

82
00:08:23,305 --> 00:08:26,610
Virtually all meditation teachers are monks and nuns.

83
00:08:26,850 --> 00:08:33,100
You do get lay people, but it's almost considered an encroachment on the monk's role.

84
00:08:34,222 --> 00:08:40,172
The people who know about the Dharma, who study the Dharma, and who teach the Dharma, are, for the most part, monks and nuns.

85
00:08:42,379 --> 00:08:53,933
And the ones who live by way of that relationship of arms taking are the monks and nuns.

86
00:08:54,615 --> 00:09:07,792
Now, the Buddha wanted that relationship, so I'm coming back to this whole idea about relationship, about attitude, about love.

87
00:09:08,932 --> 00:09:12,116
He didn't want the monks and nuns to be self-supportive.

88
00:09:12,804 --> 00:09:24,763
He wanted them to continue to be arms takers, to be dependent on lay people for their well-being, for everything they have, to be dependent on lay people.

89
00:09:25,583 --> 00:09:39,125
And what was the other side of the gift was that lay people would go to the monks for spiritual advice, for spiritual teachings.

90
00:09:39,144 --> 00:09:40,466
So there was that sort of,

91
00:09:41,003 --> 00:09:42,846
Economy of generosity.

92
00:09:43,267 --> 00:09:46,172
The one gave to the other as and when was needed.

93
00:09:47,554 --> 00:09:56,851
And of course, there's this whole idea of karma that by giving, by generosity, you accumulate goodness power.

94
00:09:57,153 --> 00:10:08,368
Now, I know that many people in the East do conceptualize it into some sort of bank account so that when you die, you go to a beautiful heaven because you gave all this food to monks.

95
00:10:08,388 --> 00:10:16,398
But the basic psychology is correct because remember, whenever you're generous, you're giving something up that you could have used for yourself.

96
00:10:18,620 --> 00:10:20,903
Giving up some of your wealth, giving up some of your time.

97
00:10:21,544 --> 00:10:23,768
And to do that is renunciation.

98
00:10:24,607 --> 00:10:28,854
So the process of liberation is the process of renunciation.

99
00:10:29,995 --> 00:10:32,258
Don't confuse that with self-mortification.

100
00:10:32,339 --> 00:10:36,043
Renunciation means letting go of attachments.

101
00:10:36,063 --> 00:10:41,510
So every time you give something, you're making a step towards your own liberation.

102
00:10:42,451 --> 00:10:54,008
And in the commentaries, it makes it clear that the process of generosity leads to liberation by way of renouncing what you would have used for your own personal satisfactions

103
00:10:54,611 --> 00:10:58,356
and joy, and giving it to somebody else.

104
00:10:58,376 --> 00:11:04,966
So, as you do that, your goodness power, that's the proper translation of punya, your goodness power grows.

105
00:11:05,788 --> 00:11:11,275
And that goodness power manifests in your growing desire to liberate yourself from suffering.

106
00:11:13,438 --> 00:11:13,678
Yeah?

107
00:11:14,961 --> 00:11:22,812
Now, we have a situation in the West, where, actually, some of the best teachers are lay people.

108
00:11:23,854 --> 00:11:24,214
And,

109
00:11:24,750 --> 00:11:28,894
And that most of the monks and nuns either can't teach or don't want to.

110
00:11:30,655 --> 00:11:31,836
Which is true also in the East.

111
00:11:32,597 --> 00:11:35,580
It's not as though just because you become a monastic you're going to be a great teacher.

112
00:11:35,639 --> 00:11:36,922
Far from it.

113
00:11:36,942 --> 00:11:38,023
And you might not want to.

114
00:11:38,643 --> 00:11:40,565
There's other roles you can play within the order.

115
00:11:41,365 --> 00:11:42,807
And you might not want to anyway.

116
00:11:42,826 --> 00:11:43,868
You don't have to play a role.

117
00:11:45,208 --> 00:11:54,657
When it comes to academic, the understanding of the scriptures and what not, there's massive, brilliant work being done by academics.

118
00:11:55,462 --> 00:12:01,909
some of the best books on Buddhism now, written by people who are PhDs, etc., etc.

119
00:12:01,929 --> 00:12:02,890
They're not monks at all.

120
00:12:03,130 --> 00:12:06,774
They don't belong to a monastic order.

121
00:12:07,355 --> 00:12:24,693
So, two of these major roles that are played by monastics in the East, of being the teachers of the actual practice and the teachers of the teaching, of the actual teaching of the Buddha, has been, as you were, taken away by lay people.

122
00:12:25,720 --> 00:12:29,164
So now there comes a real problem.

123
00:12:30,005 --> 00:12:34,091
Why do you want to support a monk?

124
00:12:34,111 --> 00:12:37,056
Since the economy of generosity has now disappeared.

125
00:12:39,038 --> 00:12:42,844
I'm still dependent on you, but you're no longer dependent on me.

126
00:12:44,365 --> 00:12:48,110
So there's something undermining that interdependency.

127
00:12:48,991 --> 00:12:50,214
There was a fair swap there.

128
00:12:50,735 --> 00:12:55,221
You fed me and I told you how to practice vipassana.

129
00:12:55,976 --> 00:12:59,542
Now, let's be careful because this comes a bit like a business deal.

130
00:13:01,004 --> 00:13:06,793
So what would you think might be other reasons why you might support a monastic?

131
00:13:08,654 --> 00:13:16,385
Now, if you take a Christian position, the monastic orders, beginning with Benedictine, had to look after themselves.

132
00:13:16,485 --> 00:13:18,389
So they separated out of society.

133
00:13:19,210 --> 00:13:20,932
This meant that there was a cleavage.

134
00:13:21,754 --> 00:13:25,899
The monks were way over there up in the hills having a great time

135
00:13:26,302 --> 00:13:27,263
and we were down here.

136
00:13:27,322 --> 00:13:29,666
But we didn't have to support them, and they didn't have to teach us.

137
00:13:29,686 --> 00:13:30,346
They're fine.

138
00:13:31,267 --> 00:13:42,240
But the belief was, of course, that they're doing a lot of prayer, and especially these enclosed orders, they're praying for the world, and there's a belief that that is doing good.

139
00:13:44,442 --> 00:13:48,025
Then you get this amazing saint, Saint Francis.

140
00:13:49,006 --> 00:13:55,413
When I saw his patchwork robe made out of sackcloth, that was quite a little moment for me.

141
00:13:55,832 --> 00:14:06,749
So here was a man and the people who followed him out of St. Clair, who went right back to that absolute poverty and depended upon lay people for their well-being.

142
00:14:06,769 --> 00:14:10,674
Although the early friars could work.

143
00:14:10,735 --> 00:14:14,260
They could do work and get money for it, labor.

144
00:14:17,085 --> 00:14:23,815
And the connection there between friars and the lay people was immediate.

145
00:14:26,123 --> 00:14:34,092
So, coming back to the Buddhist order in the West, there is this bit of a problem, you see.

146
00:14:34,513 --> 00:14:44,105
And especially if Western people haven't really taken on the idea of building up a little piggy bank so you get to a better place when you die.

147
00:14:45,847 --> 00:14:48,530
Most people are very iffy about that.

148
00:14:48,551 --> 00:14:54,097
First of all, the whole idea of a bank account and the whole idea that you're going to go anywhere after death is very iffy.

149
00:14:54,557 --> 00:14:55,860
I mean, you know.

150
00:14:57,157 --> 00:14:57,898
Supposedly you don't.

151
00:14:58,479 --> 00:14:59,801
And I've given all this stuff away.

152
00:15:01,123 --> 00:15:02,565
I mean, that's fair.

153
00:15:03,225 --> 00:15:16,166
So there's a whole area here of having to relocate, of having to find some reason as to why a lay person might support a monastic.

154
00:15:16,186 --> 00:15:20,373
Now when the order went to China, you see, beggars looked down upon you.

155
00:15:20,393 --> 00:15:21,274
You could not beg.

156
00:15:21,676 --> 00:15:29,028
So a famous abbot, whose name I forget of course, said, no work, no food.

157
00:15:30,330 --> 00:15:33,654
So in China, the monks began to grow their own food.

158
00:15:34,115 --> 00:15:46,535
And there's a lovely little film called White Clouds, something White Clouds, where this American has gone to China and he's gotten to know these Buddhist monks way up in the hills, who knows where they are.

159
00:15:47,072 --> 00:15:53,844
And there they are, they're planting their own little crops and living secluded lives up in the hills.

160
00:15:53,864 --> 00:15:56,707
And every so often they come down into the village to collect stuff.

161
00:15:57,809 --> 00:16:02,878
I don't know whether they receive it by generosity or not.

162
00:16:02,898 --> 00:16:09,388
So you can see that the order had to change there in terms of looking after itself, really.

163
00:16:09,508 --> 00:16:13,455
But in so doing, lost its connection with lay people.

164
00:16:13,975 --> 00:16:14,937
There wasn't that...

165
00:16:15,793 --> 00:16:17,995
that exchange anymore of generosity.

166
00:16:19,618 --> 00:16:24,902
So, why would you want to support me if I didn't teach?

167
00:16:24,961 --> 00:16:38,294
If you knew that I was just in this little hut in the middle of Wales, messing about, doing a bit of meditation, reading, and I turn up at your doorstep with a bowl.

168
00:16:39,416 --> 00:16:40,096
What would you say?

169
00:16:40,116 --> 00:16:41,937
What do you want?

170
00:16:41,957 --> 00:16:43,860
What's this about?

171
00:16:45,544 --> 00:16:46,365
And that often happened.

172
00:16:46,385 --> 00:16:47,187
It happened to the Buddha.

173
00:16:48,509 --> 00:16:51,293
Some Brahmin really berated him and said, you know, you're useless.

174
00:16:51,312 --> 00:16:52,274
You don't do anything.

175
00:16:52,293 --> 00:16:53,816
You come here and you're begging for food.

176
00:16:53,836 --> 00:16:54,496
Who the hell are you?

177
00:16:55,597 --> 00:16:57,380
And the Buddha said, well, thank you for the present.

178
00:16:57,480 --> 00:16:59,504
I offer it back to you.

179
00:16:59,524 --> 00:17:01,245
So he went on his way.

180
00:17:02,006 --> 00:17:08,375
So it wasn't as though everywhere Buddhist monks they were, they were thought to be worthy of donation.

181
00:17:10,538 --> 00:17:13,442
So I'd like to offer you one or two examples

182
00:17:14,873 --> 00:17:44,137
well I'll give you one reason why you should support me in my little hut up in the Brecon Beacons in the middle of winter if you look upon a monastery as a spiritual hospital so your body can be diseased and we're very happy to help people overcome physical diseases we have no problem with that there are mental illnesses

183
00:17:44,589 --> 00:17:51,038
And we're very happy to help people who we see are mentally disturbed and need help.

184
00:17:51,058 --> 00:17:54,584
So now, there are spiritual diseases.

185
00:17:55,224 --> 00:18:02,615
And by which I mean those people who are longing for liberation from suffering.

186
00:18:03,195 --> 00:18:13,630
Who actually feel their suffering strong enough whereby life as we generally know it has become meaningless.

187
00:18:13,650 --> 00:18:13,769
Right?

188
00:18:14,240 --> 00:18:21,615
So one of the signs of somebody who's moving towards a spiritual life is to realize the meaninglessness of life.

189
00:18:23,017 --> 00:18:23,979
What's the point of living?

190
00:18:32,576 --> 00:18:34,881
I mean, here we are, we've been born.

191
00:18:35,182 --> 00:18:36,403
We haven't a clue where we're going.

192
00:18:38,045 --> 00:18:39,626
We fill our lives with doing.

193
00:18:40,909 --> 00:18:47,136
We give ourselves a sense of purpose by doing something for others because others say how wonderful we are.

194
00:18:48,538 --> 00:18:53,203
And looking back in the old comedian saying, life's hard and then you die.

195
00:18:55,626 --> 00:18:55,707
See?

196
00:18:55,727 --> 00:18:58,009
So, meaninglessness.

197
00:18:59,050 --> 00:19:02,234
Like life, it's an existential thing.

198
00:19:02,468 --> 00:19:10,295
crisis that we may come across where we find that there's no reason for living.

199
00:19:10,355 --> 00:19:11,915
There's no reason for our lives.

200
00:19:12,576 --> 00:19:15,318
Because in the end, you disappear, you die.

201
00:19:15,378 --> 00:19:16,840
That's the end of it.

202
00:19:16,861 --> 00:19:21,785
So that sense of meaninglessness moves towards despair.

203
00:19:22,184 --> 00:19:30,972
It moves towards the existentialist philosophers like Albert Camus who felt that, well, you know,

204
00:19:31,190 --> 00:19:31,951
We've got life.

205
00:19:32,372 --> 00:19:35,976
Evening can be merry because tomorrow you die.

206
00:19:36,257 --> 00:19:36,916
That's the end of that.

207
00:19:38,439 --> 00:19:46,410
So people in the West who normally turn up with a spiritual disease have come across this emptiness.

208
00:19:46,930 --> 00:19:49,634
Emptiness meaning meaninglessness of their lives.

209
00:19:50,714 --> 00:19:55,340
And somehow there's something in them which says, well, I don't believe it.

210
00:19:55,801 --> 00:19:57,483
I don't believe that life exists.

211
00:19:57,768 --> 00:20:27,031
is purposeless that there is something that there is some purpose in it and the purpose cannot be out there the purpose cannot be out there because at some point i'm going to have to turn into myself and die so the purpose must be within me somewhere and that's your spiritual search so that's the buddha you see the buddha is living in an age where he uh where the obsession was rebirthed

212
00:20:28,548 --> 00:20:52,092
constant rebirth how to get out of this constant rebirth you know if you did something wrong you might be reborn as a dog and then the next life you're born as a human being and the next life you're born into a happy realm then you fall from that and you come back as a human being so one of the terrors of the age was was this idea that you'd be constantly reborn how could you get out of that in any permanent way

213
00:20:52,814 --> 00:20:57,221
And there were a few people believed in, you know, were materialists.

214
00:20:57,261 --> 00:20:59,003
They believed that when you die, that's the end of it.

215
00:20:59,726 --> 00:21:01,929
There was also that belief going on.

216
00:21:01,949 --> 00:21:10,644
But there was also this search for something which was beyond this constant samsara, this constant onward going.

217
00:21:11,325 --> 00:21:14,130
And so when he left on his search...

218
00:21:14,431 --> 00:21:17,634
he would have been in that state of meaninglessness.

219
00:21:17,755 --> 00:21:20,597
He would have also been in a state of existential crisis.

220
00:21:21,178 --> 00:21:37,536
And it manifests in the tale, the legend of him seeing somebody sick, somebody old, somebody dying, somebody dead, a corpse, and somebody sitting under a tree, a salmoner, a mendicant sitting under a tree.

221
00:21:38,005 --> 00:21:42,909
And all the time it's put in this sort of mythological way that he asks, you know, what is this?

222
00:21:42,949 --> 00:21:45,191
He's never seen this sort of thing before.

223
00:21:45,551 --> 00:21:46,491
Does it happen to me?

224
00:21:46,551 --> 00:21:47,472
Yes.

225
00:21:47,894 --> 00:21:48,993
Sickness, aging and death.

226
00:21:49,375 --> 00:21:51,836
And then the possibility of some sort of answer.

227
00:21:52,917 --> 00:21:56,161
So that's what really a monastery is about.

228
00:21:56,201 --> 00:22:07,049
Or a collection of people who gather together for spiritual purpose is to find what reason there is for living, for being alive.

229
00:22:07,839 --> 00:22:11,083
And worse, what's the reason for dying?

230
00:22:12,724 --> 00:22:14,166
Is there a purpose in our death?

231
00:22:15,989 --> 00:22:28,281
So I hope you continue to put some money in the box so that eventually I can escape to the Brecon Beacons in my little hut, knowing full well that there's always going to be a plate of spaghetti for me when I get down the hill.

232
00:22:32,286 --> 00:22:34,167
So now, coming back on that,

233
00:22:34,486 --> 00:22:41,292
we have this whole problem of, not problem, we have this whole idea of Sangha, community, right, community.

234
00:22:41,854 --> 00:22:48,800
This is, of course, really weighted in all religious traditions, not only religious traditions, humanistic traditions, any tradition.

235
00:22:49,801 --> 00:23:02,535
And there's a lovely little saying here when the Buddha says, in the discourse, which is the last moments of his life before he dies, and he says to Ananda that I

236
00:23:02,853 --> 00:23:10,123
I feel happy because I've established the four congregations or the four, what do you call them?

237
00:23:10,222 --> 00:23:11,084
Yeah, congregations.

238
00:23:12,685 --> 00:23:15,990
The monks, the nuns, the lay women and the lay men.

239
00:23:16,810 --> 00:23:22,499
And he felt that they were now rooted well enough that they would continue with the teachings after he died.

240
00:23:23,519 --> 00:23:29,468
And when Ananda says to him at this point, he says, well, the whole of the spiritual life, he says,

241
00:23:29,768 --> 00:23:32,613
As far as he's concerned, this is Ananda talking to the Buddha.

242
00:23:33,054 --> 00:23:42,609
He says he feels that half the spiritual life is good companionship, admirable friendship, admirable camaraderie.

243
00:23:42,630 --> 00:23:44,874
And the Buddha says, oh no, Ananda.

244
00:23:44,894 --> 00:23:46,696
He says it's the whole of the spiritual life.

245
00:23:47,403 --> 00:23:50,846
The whole of the spiritual life is this interdependency.

246
00:23:51,487 --> 00:23:57,031
It's the whole idea that you're not on your own and that you do need other people.

247
00:23:57,491 --> 00:23:58,732
It's not just the other teacher.

248
00:23:59,074 --> 00:24:02,336
You need other people to support you in your practice.

249
00:24:02,356 --> 00:24:04,117
That's why we come together here now.

250
00:24:04,558 --> 00:24:07,781
We formed a sangha and we're helping each other.

251
00:24:08,221 --> 00:24:09,083
There's no need to speak.

252
00:24:09,103 --> 00:24:09,983
There's no need to talk.

253
00:24:11,025 --> 00:24:14,768
It's something that's happening within us and yet it's so easy for us.

254
00:24:14,887 --> 00:24:16,650
It's much easier, shall I say, for us

255
00:24:16,900 --> 00:24:19,663
when we know that everybody else in the room is also suffering.

256
00:24:21,887 --> 00:24:32,023
It's much easier to sit here with all this pain and horror, knowing that somebody else right next door to me, sitting right here, is probably going through worse.

257
00:24:33,046 --> 00:24:35,490
Mind you, we normally think that they're having a great time.

258
00:24:36,090 --> 00:24:38,734
You come in here and everybody's sitting like this, and you think, oh my goodness.

259
00:24:41,179 --> 00:24:43,261
So that's the accent the Buddha puts on

260
00:24:44,271 --> 00:24:47,797
friendship when it comes to the spiritual life.

261
00:24:47,817 --> 00:25:00,195
And if you consider now, if you were a Muslim living in somewhere like Saudi Arabia, and you just wanted to follow those five hours, those five times a day when you wanted to pray.

262
00:25:00,977 --> 00:25:04,843
And right there, in the middle of your coffee break, you got your mat out and off you went.

263
00:25:05,463 --> 00:25:07,287
And everybody thought, oh, that's a good idea.

264
00:25:07,606 --> 00:25:08,429
And they all joined you.

265
00:25:08,709 --> 00:25:11,393
Can you imagine doing that in London?

266
00:25:11,878 --> 00:25:12,559
or in Dublin.

267
00:25:12,960 --> 00:25:24,036
Imagine getting your mat out in the middle of a work pit, in the middle of a factory, or a workplace, and just saying, well, I'm just going to do my prayers now.

268
00:25:24,056 --> 00:25:32,728
So you can see that to live in a society which has lost that general grounding for the spiritual life, it makes it just that much more difficult for us.

269
00:25:33,788 --> 00:25:37,413
Just when we want to maintain mindfulness, when we want to

270
00:25:37,681 --> 00:25:43,507
not to go out and get drunk, etc., etc., and party and all that, you're considered unsociable.

271
00:25:44,808 --> 00:25:55,460
Part of our behavior becomes unsociable because we're not actually joining in the sort of regular behavior of people who don't really have any spiritual vein in their lives.

272
00:25:55,559 --> 00:25:58,282
They don't quite know where they're going with that.

273
00:25:58,784 --> 00:26:01,105
All their practices is within their work.

274
00:26:01,666 --> 00:26:02,788
And it might be good work, too.

275
00:26:02,827 --> 00:26:06,692
It's not as though work itself is undermined because

276
00:26:06,924 --> 00:26:11,070
your good work is undermined because you don't believe in a spiritual life, far from it.

277
00:26:11,853 --> 00:26:21,768
But you can see that because you don't have that immediate companionship, your practice is constantly undermined by the surroundings you're in.

278
00:26:25,933 --> 00:26:27,737
So it means you have to work a bit harder.

279
00:26:30,401 --> 00:26:33,085
Now, going back to friendship, you see,

280
00:26:37,299 --> 00:26:57,405
Just to quote another quote that the Buddha says, with regard to external factors, I don't envisage any other single factor like admirable friendship as doing so much for someone in training who has not attained the heart's goal but remains intent on the unsurpassable safety from bondage.

281
00:26:57,425 --> 00:27:03,054
Someone who is a friend with admirable people abandons what is unskillful and develops what is skillful.

282
00:27:03,615 --> 00:27:04,776
I mean, that's the point of a friend.

283
00:27:05,531 --> 00:27:11,121
They will support you when you're being skillful and not support you when you're being unskillful.

284
00:27:11,141 --> 00:27:12,643
And therefore, you get that support.

285
00:27:13,584 --> 00:27:17,891
When you read the scriptures, by the way, I mean, I've translated it as somebody.

286
00:27:17,931 --> 00:27:18,711
It's always monk.

287
00:27:19,553 --> 00:27:25,261
But the commentaries tell us that this stands for anybody who's listening to the Dharma.

288
00:27:27,789 --> 00:27:29,510
It's like the phrase, all hands on deck.

289
00:27:29,632 --> 00:27:31,173
What is it, a synecdoche?

290
00:27:31,813 --> 00:27:34,675
Come on, where's your school?

291
00:27:34,976 --> 00:27:44,544
And when it comes to the lay people, there are a few discourses where the Buddha's explaining how we ought to live.

292
00:27:45,365 --> 00:27:50,489
And here he is talking to lay people.

293
00:27:51,390 --> 00:27:53,231
And what is meant by admirable friendship?

294
00:27:53,632 --> 00:27:57,375
This is the case where the lay person, in whatever town or village he may dwell,

295
00:27:57,692 --> 00:28:02,978
spends time with householders and householders' sons, young or old, who are advanced in virtue.

296
00:28:03,818 --> 00:28:06,161
He talks with them, engages them in discussions.

297
00:28:06,781 --> 00:28:25,000
He emulates consummate conviction in those who are consummate in conviction, consummate virtue in those who are consummate in virtue, consummate generosity in those who are consummate in generosity, and he emulates those who are consummate in discernment

298
00:28:25,739 --> 00:28:29,663
He emulates discernment in those who are consummates in discernment.

299
00:28:30,044 --> 00:28:32,185
This is called admirable friendship.

300
00:28:32,786 --> 00:28:36,150
In other words, seeking people out who have these virtues.

301
00:28:37,111 --> 00:28:45,700
Generosity, faith, generosity, virtue and discernment.

302
00:28:47,020 --> 00:28:48,803
Those who have confidence.

303
00:28:48,843 --> 00:28:52,287
To be with people who have confidence fills you with confidence.

304
00:28:52,891 --> 00:28:55,674
To be with people who are generous makes you want to be generous.

305
00:28:55,835 --> 00:29:00,060
To be with people who are virtuous, you naturally want to be virtuous like them.

306
00:29:00,621 --> 00:29:03,746
And people who are wise, you tend to listen to them.

307
00:29:03,766 --> 00:29:08,352
So there's his description of good friendship.

308
00:29:08,372 --> 00:29:09,153
But then he goes on.

309
00:29:09,192 --> 00:29:13,318
In another passage he says what good friendship is.

310
00:29:13,338 --> 00:29:14,420
It inspires love.

311
00:29:15,260 --> 00:29:19,066
Good friendship inspires love.

312
00:29:19,086 --> 00:29:20,347
It inspires respect.

313
00:29:20,769 --> 00:29:22,611
Good friendship inspires respect.

314
00:29:24,025 --> 00:29:25,446
It inspires emulation.

315
00:29:26,147 --> 00:29:28,309
Good friendship inspires emulation.

316
00:29:29,612 --> 00:29:30,792
A good friend listens.

317
00:29:31,294 --> 00:29:33,977
A good friend listens.

318
00:29:33,997 --> 00:29:35,618
And a good friend gives good advice.

319
00:29:36,961 --> 00:29:38,762
A good friend gives good advice.

320
00:29:39,784 --> 00:29:45,070
A good friend is able to enter into deep issues with the other.

321
00:29:45,090 --> 00:29:46,292
Enter into deep issues.

322
00:29:47,394 --> 00:29:50,758
And a good friend helps you not waste your resources.

323
00:29:52,595 --> 00:29:54,617
waste your money, waste your time.

324
00:29:55,519 --> 00:29:57,280
So here's a description of a good friend.

325
00:29:57,942 --> 00:29:59,163
But he goes on even further.

326
00:29:59,624 --> 00:30:05,270
He says, a friend gives what is hard to give.

327
00:30:07,314 --> 00:30:08,234
That's the test, isn't it?

328
00:30:08,634 --> 00:30:10,958
A friend gives what is hard to give.

329
00:30:10,998 --> 00:30:12,200
So you know your friends immediately.

330
00:30:13,981 --> 00:30:15,604
He does what is hard to do.

331
00:30:16,125 --> 00:30:18,567
A friend does what is hard to do.

332
00:30:20,336 --> 00:30:26,365
A friend has patience with harsh speech and has patience with wrongdoing.

333
00:30:27,185 --> 00:30:34,195
So if you love somebody, you have to presume they're going to hurt you.

334
00:30:34,856 --> 00:30:38,801
If you love somebody and you think they're never going to hurt you, then you're going to be very upset when they do.

335
00:30:40,451 --> 00:30:53,467
So if you presume that your friend, your family member, at some point will do something which is painful for you at whatever level, then you can easily forgive them and re-establish friendship.

336
00:30:53,926 --> 00:31:01,936
But if you think they shouldn't do that, if you think that a friend or a family member should not behave like that towards me, then that's it.

337
00:31:02,237 --> 00:31:04,019
You've cut off friendship.

338
00:31:04,038 --> 00:31:04,338
That's it.

339
00:31:04,358 --> 00:31:04,940
That's the end of it.

340
00:31:06,561 --> 00:31:07,522
Take them to court.

341
00:31:12,633 --> 00:31:18,759
A good friendship is someone whom you can confide in and someone who keeps your confidences.

342
00:31:20,442 --> 00:31:23,486
Someone you can confide in and somebody who keeps your confidences.

343
00:31:24,227 --> 00:31:27,730
That's a very deep trust, depending on what it is you're sharing.

344
00:31:28,652 --> 00:31:32,917
And often it's very helpful to talk to somebody, to talk out a problem.

345
00:31:33,298 --> 00:31:36,582
It can be relieving to the heart to share a burden with somebody.

346
00:31:37,387 --> 00:31:43,015
But you wouldn't do it if you thought they'd be off and tell the very person whom you're complaining about.

347
00:31:45,358 --> 00:31:46,319
And free of contempt.

348
00:31:46,720 --> 00:31:47,582
Free of contempt.

349
00:31:47,682 --> 00:31:49,443
Somebody who does not despise you.

350
00:31:50,184 --> 00:31:54,990
Somebody who may envy you but does not act upon it.

351
00:31:55,071 --> 00:32:00,278
Somebody who may feel an occasional jealousy but does not act upon it.

352
00:32:00,999 --> 00:32:04,124
So these are good pointers, aren't they?

353
00:32:04,144 --> 00:32:04,723
Don't you think so?

354
00:32:05,905 --> 00:32:06,686
I rather like them.

355
00:32:09,231 --> 00:32:10,973
points out the difficulty of friendship.

356
00:32:11,693 --> 00:32:24,926
So, sometimes, you know, we get the impression that Buddhism is really all about vipassana and meditation and basically that's what it is.

357
00:32:24,967 --> 00:32:35,576
And then we forget that there is a whole eightfold path, that the vipassana belongs to the last three, right effort, right concentration, right mindfulness.

358
00:32:36,686 --> 00:32:39,309
But that feeds into the first one, which is right understanding.

359
00:32:39,851 --> 00:32:42,914
But then once you've got right understanding, it has to become systemic.

360
00:32:43,415 --> 00:32:45,077
It has to manifest in our attitudes.

361
00:32:45,798 --> 00:32:49,423
And as soon as it begins to manifest in our attitudes, it must express itself.

362
00:32:50,144 --> 00:32:53,067
Right speech, right action, right livelihood.

363
00:32:54,088 --> 00:32:55,810
And the whole thing flows around upon itself.

364
00:32:55,912 --> 00:32:57,113
The one feeds upon the other.

365
00:32:57,433 --> 00:32:58,255
So it's a spiral.

366
00:32:58,615 --> 00:33:00,758
It keeps turning and turning.

367
00:33:00,778 --> 00:33:04,061
And in this way, within a

368
00:33:04,327 --> 00:33:10,292
a small length of time, if we practice with severe dedication, we will no doubt be liberated.

369
00:33:15,258 --> 00:33:27,749
So, I want to, before I end, I just want to have a look at these questions that you, that I didn't answer yesterday, because they're more to do with the practice.

370
00:33:27,769 --> 00:33:31,952
I just want to leave a bit of time too for daily practice.

371
00:33:33,433 --> 00:33:34,015
So,

372
00:33:34,450 --> 00:34:02,652
is it difficult for me to reconcile a practicing Buddhist can be a non-vegetarian vegetarianism I don't know of any Buddhist country where Buddhists don't eat meat which doesn't tell you very much it's a special practice of monks and nuns in Burma that they go through the three month season the Vasa season, the rainy season without eating meat

373
00:34:04,623 --> 00:34:08,327
The essential problem is the suffering of animals, the killing of animals.

374
00:34:09,248 --> 00:34:11,449
And it depends upon your connection with that.

375
00:34:12,291 --> 00:34:14,472
Obviously when you're eating the meat you're not killing the animal.

376
00:34:14,672 --> 00:34:16,155
If anything you're suffering from greed.

377
00:34:16,715 --> 00:34:20,818
But you're definitely not suffering from aversion or hatred or anything like that.

378
00:34:20,838 --> 00:34:30,409
But it's making that connection really that when you buy something you're going back to support the abattoir, you're going back to support the killer of the animal.

379
00:34:31,070 --> 00:34:34,393
And so it's up to your own sensibility really as to where

380
00:34:34,795 --> 00:34:37,538
as to where you feel you can place yourself in that order.

381
00:34:38,880 --> 00:34:43,425
But in Buddhist understanding, all sentient beings suffer one way or the other.

382
00:34:44,425 --> 00:34:46,387
And so it's up to the individual to decide.

383
00:34:47,048 --> 00:34:49,791
Now, there are some people who actually have to eat meat.

384
00:34:51,414 --> 00:34:57,681
I know somebody who has, I think, something like half a kidney or something.

385
00:34:58,606 --> 00:35:03,972
And the only way they're going to survive is by... And the body won't accept pulses and stuff like that.

386
00:35:04,373 --> 00:35:05,134
It's by eating chicken.

387
00:35:06,014 --> 00:35:13,704
So, there is this view that if it's for health reasons, then, you know, then you should feel okay about that.

388
00:35:14,184 --> 00:35:15,967
And there, of course, are situations in the world.

389
00:35:16,507 --> 00:35:20,452
If you live in the Arctic, you're hardly going to grow wheat, are you?

390
00:35:20,472 --> 00:35:22,335
If you live in desert, you're going to eat a goat.

391
00:35:22,737 --> 00:35:23,418
What are you going to do?

392
00:35:24,259 --> 00:35:26,722
If you live in Wales, it's bad enough.

393
00:35:28,344 --> 00:35:29,865
Somebody wants you to keep sheep.

394
00:35:30,507 --> 00:35:31,789
What can you grow in Wales?

395
00:35:33,931 --> 00:35:38,016
If you're up on the Brecon Beacons, it's pretty deserted up there.

396
00:35:39,077 --> 00:35:41,942
So, remember that the Buddha is very pragmatic.

397
00:35:42,443 --> 00:35:43,864
There's no ism.

398
00:35:44,405 --> 00:35:47,869
He wouldn't have agreed with vegetarian ism.

399
00:35:48,650 --> 00:35:51,715
Because idealism doesn't fit in a world

400
00:35:52,132 --> 00:35:54,735
which is obviously relative.

401
00:35:56,038 --> 00:35:58,981
All our morality is relative, it's circumstantial.

402
00:36:00,784 --> 00:36:10,657
You can make a declaration of not to kill anybody, but I'm sure you can think of occasions when you'd have felt quite justified in killing somebody.

403
00:36:12,239 --> 00:36:13,782
Not to take what is not freely given.

404
00:36:13,822 --> 00:36:17,786
You remember the old thing that you get at school about, if you're dead hungry, can you steal a loaf?

405
00:36:18,442 --> 00:36:25,670
So once you realize that morality is circumstantial, it's all to do with the situation you're in, etc.

406
00:36:26,210 --> 00:36:28,353
You know that one about the...

407
00:36:31,336 --> 00:36:32,898
If I can remember it right now.

408
00:36:32,918 --> 00:36:33,679
You might have heard this.

409
00:36:33,699 --> 00:36:35,902
This is one of these silly thought experiments.

410
00:36:36,722 --> 00:36:40,246
You're on a bridge with a very, very big fat man.

411
00:36:41,969 --> 00:36:43,170
And there's a train coming along.

412
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:46,474
And there are people working on the tracks.

413
00:36:47,972 --> 00:36:52,878
And you can see that this train is going to hit these people.

414
00:36:54,300 --> 00:37:00,186
One way, about five or six people.

415
00:37:01,027 --> 00:37:08,414
But if you push the man off, it'll derail the train and save five people.

416
00:37:08,434 --> 00:37:12,539
Now, will you push him off?

417
00:37:12,559 --> 00:37:14,161
It's a dilemma, I hope.

418
00:37:14,181 --> 00:37:15,481
None of us have to face it.

419
00:37:19,731 --> 00:37:24,155
It's examples like that that show you that morality can be quite circumstantial.

420
00:37:26,818 --> 00:37:29,340
So yes, it's up to a person to decide that.

421
00:37:30,061 --> 00:37:36,407
I have a meditator who comes quite very often and she simply cannot eat pulses and beans.

422
00:37:36,427 --> 00:37:37,329
She just won't take it.

423
00:37:38,429 --> 00:37:43,494
So she normally brings sardines or something with her if she's on a week-long retreat.

424
00:37:44,014 --> 00:37:45,856
So there's also health reasons.

425
00:37:46,157 --> 00:37:49,563
And of course, there is the understanding that nature feeds off itself.

426
00:37:50,204 --> 00:37:54,710
There's a YouTube.

427
00:37:55,291 --> 00:38:03,844
If you type in Yellowstone and you come up with Monbiot, who's this writer.

428
00:38:04,846 --> 00:38:06,869
Do you know who I'm talking about, Monbiot?

429
00:38:06,889 --> 00:38:07,690
He's not that well known.

430
00:38:08,070 --> 00:38:12,637
And he's very much into wilding, wilding the old places.

431
00:38:13,141 --> 00:38:22,193
And the video shows you how the introduction of about 20 or 30 wolves completely changed the ecology of Yellowstone Park.

432
00:38:22,634 --> 00:38:24,697
I mean, right, now what's he introducing?

433
00:38:24,797 --> 00:38:26,519
He's introducing an animal that eats another animal.

434
00:38:27,320 --> 00:38:30,324
So you have to understand that, you know, nature feeds off itself.

435
00:38:32,487 --> 00:38:39,637
So really, you know, it just comes back to us really and our particular situation in this society where

436
00:38:40,208 --> 00:39:05,574
you know vegetarianism is very easy to get hold of you can be a vegan without any problem if you want it to so does it ever get easier with the meditation no that's an easy question if you keep practicing over years guess what for me it seemed easier to meditate when I started now it seems harder after a few retreats dead on

437
00:39:07,175 --> 00:39:36,387
because the main reason is that you're digging deeper you know I mean when you come to meditation you come with beginner's mind and you sit there and you're full of vigour and interest and then like anything else it gets boring you know who the hell wants to watch their breath what the daft think they'll do anyway and then there's and then there's and then the stuff starts coming up so that purification you just can't you can't get anywhere without going through it it's full stop that's it's just part and parcel of the course and the break

438
00:39:37,516 --> 00:39:44,965
But generally speaking, of course, you look back and you think, well, you know, life's changed, my attitude has changed, life's just a little bit easier.

439
00:39:45,146 --> 00:39:47,949
But that doesn't mean to say it's going to be always like that, because you've got them down.

440
00:39:48,751 --> 00:39:49,751
Spiritual life's like that.

441
00:39:51,034 --> 00:39:52,396
Sometimes you think you're getting nowhere.

442
00:39:53,016 --> 00:39:56,740
And then when that crisis passes, you find you've moved to a slightly different level.

443
00:39:57,681 --> 00:39:58,503
So don't give up hope.

444
00:40:00,226 --> 00:40:01,126
Not yet, anyway.

445
00:40:02,677 --> 00:40:05,382
How to establish a daily meditation practice in your life.

446
00:40:06,384 --> 00:40:10,811
So, it really is, I think, important to meditate a little in the morning.

447
00:40:13,335 --> 00:40:24,516
And it's, if you can, to do one in the evening, but especially when you come back from a day out or a day's work, before you eat, after you eat you fall asleep.

448
00:40:25,592 --> 00:40:36,206
The first, the beginning of the day is when you set your weather then, where you actually remind yourself you want to maintain this level of awareness, you know, affectionate awareness, to be awake to what's happening.

449
00:40:37,389 --> 00:40:52,347
And when you come back from a day, just to let whatever you've accumulated in that day just to arise, little aversions, little irritations, little anxieties, just let them come up and clear themselves out.

450
00:40:52,849 --> 00:40:54,351
And then you have a much more sort of,

451
00:40:54,735 --> 00:41:23,206
restful evening and on top of that you know to stop everything a little bit before you go to sleep you know it's not there's no point in in launching yourself in the bed after two hours on facebook or having watched the latest crime drama and then thinking you're gonna have deep sleep well you may have of course but but generally speaking it's best to sort of calm down you know play play some music read poetry do something which which brings the whole system down so when you fall asleep

452
00:41:23,608 --> 00:41:27,672
You're taking that beauty, that beautiful mental state with you.

453
00:41:28,313 --> 00:41:31,077
And that's how you feel more refreshed, I think.

454
00:41:32,838 --> 00:41:35,081
There's no easy way to establish a daily practice.

455
00:41:35,101 --> 00:41:39,726
You've got to establish a real religious commitment.

456
00:41:39,965 --> 00:41:44,311
So you have to say to yourself, right, I can definitely do 20 minutes every morning.

457
00:41:45,411 --> 00:41:46,913
So there's no reason why I can't do 20 minutes.

458
00:41:46,932 --> 00:41:48,655
If you can't think of that, then five minutes, right?

459
00:41:49,123 --> 00:41:55,875
And then you actually make that sort of absolute determination that for the next six months that's what you're going to do.

460
00:41:55,894 --> 00:41:57,682
And that's how you establish the practice.

461
00:41:58,827 --> 00:42:03,434
And then if you do it, then you have to promise yourself something like a celebratory meal.

462
00:42:04,215 --> 00:42:10,384
And if you don't, you have to promise yourself, I don't know, jump off a bridge or something.

463
00:42:10,403 --> 00:42:11,987
Something terribly wild and terrible.

464
00:42:12,467 --> 00:42:16,893
So that, you know, would stop you, would keep you at your promise.

465
00:42:17,454 --> 00:42:21,199
But really that's the thing, is to do it religiously for the length of time.

466
00:42:21,501 --> 00:42:23,063
And then it becomes an internal habit.

467
00:42:23,701 --> 00:42:25,782
And you might miss a day, you might miss two days.

468
00:42:26,184 --> 00:42:27,264
But you don't want to miss more than that.

469
00:42:27,905 --> 00:42:32,070
I remember Nori had the great ballet dancer of the 60s and 70s said that.

470
00:42:32,530 --> 00:42:34,271
If you didn't practice one day, it was fine.

471
00:42:34,773 --> 00:42:35,974
Two days, he felt it.

472
00:42:36,275 --> 00:42:38,697
Three days, everybody else did.

473
00:42:38,717 --> 00:42:45,545
So if you take that as your standard for practice, then really just keep at it.

474
00:42:46,144 --> 00:42:51,451
If you do miss it and you have to start again, just don't go into this sort of self-hate syndrome.

475
00:42:51,831 --> 00:42:53,353
I'm useless and that's all rubbish.

476
00:42:53,992 --> 00:42:54,932
Just start it again.

477
00:42:57,557 --> 00:42:58,177
It's important.

478
00:42:59,119 --> 00:43:01,523
Because that's where you accumulate, you see.

479
00:43:01,684 --> 00:43:03,226
This is your goodness.

480
00:43:03,246 --> 00:43:04,849
You accumulate the practice.

481
00:43:04,869 --> 00:43:08,534
It accumulates slowly.

482
00:43:08,554 --> 00:43:15,965
With so many varied Buddhist practices, is it best to self-teach using the original text, such as a combination of available books, audio, etc.

483
00:43:15,786 --> 00:43:15,965
?

484
00:43:17,295 --> 00:43:21,802
Yeah, obviously listening intently to your audio.

485
00:43:21,862 --> 00:43:23,405
That's me, thank you.

486
00:43:23,505 --> 00:43:26,469
In the first place, well, absolutely.

487
00:43:26,489 --> 00:43:31,018
No, I think it's important to get hold of a teacher.

488
00:43:31,659 --> 00:43:35,403
I mean, when I think of, you know, my introduction, I wouldn't.

489
00:43:35,724 --> 00:43:39,590
Well, what happened to me was I read a book on Zen Buddhism.

490
00:43:39,806 --> 00:43:41,610
I was impressed by them, though, right?

491
00:43:41,630 --> 00:43:43,773
So what I did was, I thought, I'm going to practice this.

492
00:43:43,813 --> 00:43:49,300
So I was on the way to the shops, which would have taken about, I don't know, five, seven minutes.

493
00:43:49,820 --> 00:43:52,905
So I'm walking up the road, observing myself walking up the road.

494
00:43:53,246 --> 00:43:55,688
By the time I got to the top, I thought, oh, this is going to drive me crazy.

495
00:43:56,751 --> 00:43:58,072
So I abandoned Zen Buddhism.

496
00:43:59,414 --> 00:44:04,420
Later on, through crisis and all sorts of stuff, I ended up with a Zen teacher in Birmingham.

497
00:44:04,541 --> 00:44:04,802
And...

498
00:44:05,034 --> 00:44:15,670
She came in and she sat me on the bench facing a wall, told me to keep my eyes slightly open, dead man's eyes, gave me a punch in the back so I sat up properly.

499
00:44:16,510 --> 00:44:19,456
And then her instruction was, watch whatever comes up.

500
00:44:19,476 --> 00:44:21,918
That was it, watch whatever comes up.

501
00:44:22,760 --> 00:44:27,306
And that was 40 minutes of sheer horror and pain and all that.

502
00:44:27,327 --> 00:44:34,317
But for some reason, at the end of that, I just knew this was going to get me out of the state I'd gotten myself into.

503
00:44:35,224 --> 00:44:39,972
So without that, you say, I think you've got to go somewhere.

504
00:44:39,992 --> 00:44:42,536
I think you need that personal contact.

505
00:44:44,179 --> 00:44:53,094
Even if it's only once in a while, it doesn't have to be something constant, but you need to have that personal contact from somebody whom you feel has been there.

506
00:44:54,315 --> 00:44:59,804
It's like if you climb a mountain, who are you going to get advice off, a geologist or a mountaineer?

507
00:45:01,588 --> 00:45:01,688
Yeah.

508
00:45:05,431 --> 00:45:14,099
So yes, Buddhism involves considerable self-awareness and concentrated practice that many, for various reasons, are not in a position to do.

509
00:45:17,101 --> 00:45:19,242
Their mindset, mental health issues, etc.

510
00:45:19,884 --> 00:45:22,967
So, is it only for the select few?

511
00:45:23,686 --> 00:45:28,612
Well, it's true to say that Vipassana isn't good for somebody who's mentally ill.

512
00:45:29,932 --> 00:45:34,577
In the East, if you turn up at a monastery with an obvious sign of mental illness, depression or

513
00:45:35,266 --> 00:45:36,827
They just give you metta practice.

514
00:45:36,967 --> 00:45:39,110
They don't give you vipassana.

515
00:45:39,791 --> 00:45:45,777
But anybody who's in an ordinary state of madness can practice vipassana.

516
00:45:46,237 --> 00:45:46,898
And what's the problem?

517
00:45:50,922 --> 00:45:54,065
I mean, we're all, at one level or another, crazy.

518
00:45:56,088 --> 00:45:57,190
So, yes, it's...

519
00:45:57,750 --> 00:46:04,918
I mean, that's why this mindfulness has been so successful, really, because of that.

520
00:46:05,253 --> 00:46:13,282
I mean, it's used as a psychotherapeutic intervention and therefore takes away its spiritual purpose.

521
00:46:13,302 --> 00:46:26,641
But for the occasional purpose, for the occasional person, just those introductions, just that simple introduction, understanding how suffering is caused, may very well open the spiritual gates for them.

522
00:46:26,661 --> 00:46:34,550
So, you know, just because it's being taught as a psychotherapeutic intervention doesn't mean it might not have

523
00:46:35,425 --> 00:46:39,371
a spiritual effect on the person.

524
00:46:39,452 --> 00:46:40,313
It's not taught like that.

525
00:46:40,333 --> 00:46:48,286
It's not taught with, generally speaking, it's not taught with any moral instructions with it.

526
00:46:49,068 --> 00:46:53,054
But of course there is a presumed morality in it of compassion.

527
00:46:57,543 --> 00:47:01,128
Some Buddhist teachers are a bit negative about it, but I don't

528
00:47:01,818 --> 00:47:02,659
You don't see a problem really.

529
00:47:02,679 --> 00:47:04,561
It's a bit like yoga, you know, body beautiful.

530
00:47:04,802 --> 00:47:05,483
What's wrong with that?

531
00:47:06,585 --> 00:47:09,429
You miss out on all the rest of it, but at least you've got a beautiful body.

532
00:47:11,693 --> 00:47:13,135
That'll do.

533
00:47:15,059 --> 00:47:28,780
Is Buddhism like the major religions of the world who see women as inferior?

534
00:47:29,201 --> 00:47:30,001
Please say no.

535
00:47:30,673 --> 00:47:57,929
well according to the teachings of the Buddha women seem to be able to become fully liberated like men what society does with that is something else I think you can say just looking across the ancient just looking across the Asian world

536
00:48:00,762 --> 00:48:04,547
Islam, Hinduism and Buddhism.

537
00:48:05,148 --> 00:48:09,273
Where you find Buddhism, I think you find much more equality.

538
00:48:10,434 --> 00:48:13,557
Women in Buddhist countries are equally doctors, etc.

539
00:48:13,599 --> 00:48:18,264
The first prime minister was the prime minister of Sri Lanka.

540
00:48:18,284 --> 00:48:19,445
What was her name?

541
00:48:19,485 --> 00:48:20,086
Bandranaga.

542
00:48:24,552 --> 00:48:26,715
But, I mean, this is ancient stuff.

543
00:48:26,956 --> 00:48:28,777
Patriarchy is embedded in

544
00:48:31,356 --> 00:48:32,237
Come the revolution.

545
00:48:34,880 --> 00:48:35,661
So you're not...

546
00:48:35,681 --> 00:48:41,367
I mean, it comes through the scriptures, which is unfortunate.

547
00:48:43,851 --> 00:48:45,293
But you don't...

548
00:48:45,313 --> 00:48:46,233
I don't see the Buddha.

549
00:48:50,938 --> 00:49:00,250
If you read, for instance, the verses left by the elders, both the men and the women, the monks and the nuns, and also lay people, you can see that...

550
00:49:02,052 --> 00:49:13,061
some of the women were just as fully liberated as the men, and just as much praised and seen as teachers as the monks.

551
00:49:14,463 --> 00:49:15,463
The monks sought them out.

552
00:49:18,485 --> 00:49:21,789
So yes, we're stuck with history, I'm afraid.

553
00:49:24,311 --> 00:49:31,097
These days, if you look across the Vipassana teacher scene, women are probably in the majority.

554
00:49:38,333 --> 00:49:43,300
Is that a good sign?

555
00:49:43,320 --> 00:49:44,742
Are we returning to matriarchy?

556
00:49:45,802 --> 00:49:46,384
Heavens above.

557
00:49:49,608 --> 00:49:51,831
I shall leave you with that thought.

558
00:49:51,851 --> 00:49:54,875
I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance.

559
00:49:55,615 --> 00:50:03,766
That by your severe devotion to the practice you may be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

